The Marswalker then shuts its front flap to secure the robot vacuum inside, turns, and drives up or down a nearby staircase, before opening the flap again so the S2 can go about cleaning on a different floor. If it works as intended, the Marswalker could solve one of the biggest limitations of robot vacuums and allow your automated cleaner to fully traverse your multi-story home.

external.description: Lycopsids, like the 377-million-year-old fossil found at Saltern Cove, differ significantly from modern trees in similar environments (e.g., coastal or volcanic regions) due to their evolutionary stage, structure, and ecological roles. Here's a breakdown of key differences based on their characteristics and the Devonian environment:  1. Structure and Morphology    Lycopsids (Ancient Trees):      Primitive vascular plants with simple structures, lacking true leaves, branches, or deep root systems.      Had microphylls (small, scale-like leaf structures) supported by a single vein, unlike the complex leaves of modern trees.      Stems were often hollow or lightly woody, with limited secondary growth (wood production) compared to modern trees.      Reached heights of a few meters in the Devonian, though later lycopsids (e.g., Carboniferous Lepidodendron) could grow taller.      Lacked true bark; their outer layers were composed of a tough, green cortex for photosynthesis.     Modern Trees:      Possess complex structures with true leaves, extensive branching, and deep, robust root systems for stability and nutrient uptake.      Have significant secondary growth, producing thick woody tissue (xylem) and bark, allowing for greater height and longevity.      Leaves are typically broad (in angiosperms) or needle-like (in conifers), with complex vascular systems for efficient photosynthesis and water transport.  2. Reproduction    Lycopsids:      Reproduced via spores released from sporangia, often located on specialized structures like cones or along stems.      Lacked flowers, fruits, or seeds, as these evolved much later in plant history (e.g., with gymnosperms and angiosperms).      Required moist environments for spore dispersal and gametophyte development, tying them closely to wet or coastal settings.     Modern Trees:      Most reproduce via seeds (gymnosperms and angiosperms), with some using pollen and flowers (angiosperms) for more efficient reproduction.      Seeds allow for dispersal in diverse environments, including drier ones, unlike the water-dependent spores of lycopsids.      Many modern trees have adaptations like wind or animal pollination, reducing reliance on moist conditions.  3. Environmental Adaptations    Lycopsids in Devonian Environments:      Thrived in warm, humid coastal or volcanic island environments, like those indicated by the Saltern Cove fossil.      Adapted to low-oxygen soils and fluctuating water levels, often in swampy or floodplain settings.      Played a key role in stabilizing soils and contributing organic matter, helping form early soils in Devonian ecosystems.      Lacked competition from modern plants, as they were among the first large land plants.     Modern Trees in Similar Environments:      Modern trees in coastal or volcanic regions (e.g., mangroves or pioneer species on volcanic slopes) have advanced adaptations like extensive root systems to anchor in unstable soils or tolerate salinity (e.g., mangroves’ pneumatophores).      Have diverse strategies for drought resistance, nutrient uptake, and competition with other plants, fungi, and animals.      Benefit from millions of years of co-evolution with pollinators, seed dispersers, and mycorrhizal fungi, unlike the simpler ecosystems of the Devonian.  4. Ecological Role    Lycopsids:      Were pioneers in early terrestrial ecosystems, contributing to the formation of the first forests during the Devonian.      Their decomposition helped create early peat and coal deposits (especially in later Carboniferous lycopsids).      Had limited interactions with animals, as terrestrial fauna (e.g., early arthropods) were just emerging.     Modern Trees:      Play complex roles in ecosystems, supporting diverse wildlife through food, shelter, and oxygen production.      Contribute to carbon cycling and soil formation on a massive scale, with intricate relationships with fungi, bacteria, and animals.      Face competition and threats from other plants, herbivores, and human activity, unlike the relatively unchallenged lycopsids.  5. Physiological Differences    Lycopsids:      Had simpler vascular systems (tracheids) for water and nutrient transport, less efficient than modern trees’ vessels and tracheids.      Photosynthesis occurred in the cortex of stems, not just leaves, due to their primitive structure.      Were less efficient at water conservation, thriving in consistently wet environments.     Modern Trees:      Have advanced vascular systems (xylem and phloem) for efficient transport over long distances, supporting taller growth.      Possess stomata and cuticles for better water retention, allowing survival in varied climates, including arid volcanic regions. Structure and Morphology    Lycopsids (Ancient Trees):      Primitive vascular plants with simple structures, lacking true leaves, branches, or deep root systems.      Had microphylls (small, scale-like leaf structures) supported by a single vein, unlike the complex leaves of modern trees.      Stems were often hollow or lightly woody, with limited secondary growth (wood production) compared to modern trees.      Reached heights of a few meters in the Devonian, though later lycopsids (e.g., Carboniferous Lepidodendron) could grow taller. Have significant secondary growth, producing thick woody tissue (xylem) and bark, allowing for greater height and longevity.      Leaves are typically broad (in angiosperms) or needle-like (in conifers), with complex vascular systems for efficient photosynthesis and water transport.  2. Reproduction    Lycopsids:      Reproduced via spores released from sporangia, often located on specialized structures like cones or along stems.      Lacked flowers, fruits, or seeds, as these evolved much later in plant history (e.g., with gymnosperms and angiosperms).      Required moist environments for spore dispersal and gametophyte development, tying them closely to wet or coastal settings.     Modern Trees:      Most reproduce via seeds (gymnosperms and angiosperms), with some using pollen and flowers (angiosperms) for more efficient reproduction.      Seeds allow for dispersal in diverse environments, including drier ones, unlike the water-dependent spores of lycopsids.      Many modern trees have adaptations like wind or animal pollination, reducing reliance on moist conditions.  3. Had limited interactions with animals, as terrestrial fauna (e.g., early arthropods) were just emerging. Wednesday, October 29th
Advanced Systems Design in Ghost of Yötei
Sound Design & Technology
© 2:45 PM - 3:45 PM
• Academy 3
Description
This talk will highlight some of the key ways the audio team at Sucker Punch strove to push the soundscape of Ghost of Yötei through calculated tool development and systems design. Using Ghost of Tsushima as a jumping off point, we will describe the ways we improved on our existing systems and how we focused our work on doing more with less. We will highlight some of the core systems that were drastically overhauled and improved for this sequel, and do a mini-deep dive into each system, giving audience members a glimpse into our workflow, and ideas to improve their own systems.
We will pinpoint how these new systems improvements came to be, why we chose them for scrutiny, and how we overhauled them to create simpler systems that sounded better, and were easier to implement, than the previous game. Systems explored will include: situational ambience, foley, combat, and waterways. The talk will also explore how the evolution of systems propagated further and further out as the project progressed. What started as one change in one system, spidered out to add functionality across other areas of the game.
Takeaway: Audience members should come away from this talk with an understanding of how the Sucker Punch audio team crafted the soundscape of Ghost of Yotei, and have some inspirational ideas for how to roll some of these concepts into their own workflows.
Speakers
• Rev. Dr. Bradley_D Meyer, Sucker Punch Productions, Audio Director
• Josh Lord, Sucker Punch Productions - Playstation, Senior Staff
